'''The Who''' are an English [[Rock music|rock]] band formed in 1964. Their best known line-up consisted of lead singer [[Roger Daltrey]], guitarist [[Pete Townshend]], bassist [[John Entwistle]] and drummer [[Keith Moon]]. For much of their career they have been regarded as one of the three most important British rock acts along with [[the Beatles]] and [[the Rolling Stones]] and one of the [[List of best-selling music artists|world's best-selling bands of all time]], having sold more than 100 million records.<ref name="The Who">{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/the-who/biography |title=The Who |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsletter.co.uk/what-s-on/music/the-who-s-quadrophrenia-will-be-revisited-in-belfast-1-4742083|title=The Who’s Quadrophrenia will be revisited in Belfast|publisher=[[The News Letter]]|date=2013-02-01|accessdate=2013-05-21|last=The News Letter|first=Reporter}}</ref>

The Who developed from an earlier group, the Detours, before stabilising around a line-up of Daltrey, Townshend, Entwistle and Moon. After releasing a single billed as the High Numbers, the group established themselves as part of the [[mod (subculture)|mod movement]], specialising in [[auto-destructive art]] by destroying guitars and drums onstage. They achieved recognition in the UK after support by [[pirate radio]] and television, and their first single as the Who, "[[I Can't Explain]]", reached the top ten. A string of hit singles followed including "[[My Generation]]", "[[Substitute (The Who song)|Substitute]]" and "[[Happy Jack (song)|Happy Jack]]". Although initially regarded as a singles act, they also found success with the albums ''[[My Generation (album)|My Generation]]'' and ''[[A Quick One]]''. In 1967, they achieved success in the US after performing at the [[Monterey Pop Festival]], and with the top ten single "[[I Can See for Miles]]". They released ''[[The Who Sell Out]]'' at the end of the year, and spent much of 1968 touring the US.

The release of their fourth album, ''[[Tommy (album)|Tommy]]'', in 1969 was a major commercial and critical achievement. Subsequent live appearances at [[Woodstock]] and the [[Isle of Wight Festival]], along with the live album ''[[Live At Leeds]]'', transformed the Who's reputation from a hit-singles band into a critically acclaimed rock act. With their success came increased pressure on lead songwriter Townshend, and the follow-up to ''Tommy'', ''[[Lifehouse (rock opera)|Lifehouse]]'', was abandoned in favour of 1971's ''[[Who's Next]]''. The group subsequently released ''[[Quadrophenia]]'' (1973) and ''[[The Who by Numbers]]'' (1975), oversaw the [[Tommy (1975 film)|film adaptation of ''Tommy'']] and toured to large audiences before semi-retiring from live performance in 1977. The release of ''[[Who Are You]]'' in August 1978 was overshadowed by the death of Moon on 7 September, at the age of 32.

[[Kenney Jones]], formerly of [[the Small Faces]] and [[the Faces]], replaced Moon and the group resumed touring. A [[Quadrophenia (film)|film adaptation of ''Quadrophenia'']] was released in 1979 along with the retrospective documentary ''[[The Kids Are Alright (film)|The Kids Are Alright]]''. The group continued recording, releasing ''[[Face Dances]]'' in 1981 and ''[[It's Hard]]'' the following year, before breaking up. They occasionally re-formed for live appearances such as [[Live Aid]] in 1985, a 25th anniversary tour in 1989 that drew mixed reviews, and for a tour of ''Quadrophenia'' in 1996. The Who resumed regular touring in 1999, with drummer [[Zak Starkey]], to a positive response, and were considering the possibility of a new album, but these plans were stalled by Entwistle's death in June 2002 at the age of 57. Townshend and Daltrey elected to continue as the Who, releasing ''[[Endless Wire (The Who album)|Endless Wire]]'' (2006), which reached the top ten in the UK and US. The group continue to play live on a regular basis, and in 2012 they began a further tour of ''Quadrophenia''.

==History==

===Background===
[[File:TVU Campus St Marys Road.jpg|thumb|[[Pete Townshend]] attended [[Ealing Art College]] (''pictured in 2010''), and his experience there made a notable contribution to the Who's career]]

The three founding members of the Who, Daltrey, Townshend and Entwistle, all grew up in [[Acton, London]]. All three passed the [[Eleven Plus exam]] and went to [[Acton County Grammar School]].{{sfn|Marsh|1983|pp=13,19,24}} Townshend's father, Cliff, had played [[saxophone]] and his mother, Betty, had sung in the entertainment division of the [[RAF]] during [[World War II]],{{sfn|Marsh|1983|pp=15-16}} while Entwistle's father, Herbert, played [[trumpet]], and his mother, Queenie, played [[piano]].{{sfn|Marsh|1983|pp=24-25}} The pair became friends in the second year of Acton County, and formed a [[trad jazz]] group, the Confederates,{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=26}} while Entwistle also played [[french horn]] in the Middlesex Schools' Symphony Orchestra. However, both became influenced by the increasing popularity of [[rock 'n' roll]], with Townshend particularly admiring [[Cliff Richard]]'s debut single, "[[Move It]]".{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=17}} Entwistle had decided to move to guitar as his instrument of choice, but after struggling with it due to his large fingers, and on hearing the guitar work of [[Duane Eddy]], decided to move to the bass. He was unable to afford his own instrument and so built one at home.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=29}} Townshend and Entwistle both left school aged 16. Entwistle went to work with the [[Inland Revenue]], while Townshend started a course at [[Ealing Art College]],{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=20}} a move that he would subsequently describe as profoundly influential on the course of the Who.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=22}}

Daltrey, who was in the year above them, had moved to Acton from [[Shepherd's Bush]], a more working-class area. He had trouble fitting in as an outsider, and discovered gangs and rock 'n' roll.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=14}} He was expelled from school aged 15 and found work on a building site.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=11}} Daltrey maintains that his subsequent musical career saved him from a dead-end working man's job,{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=14}} and in 1959 he started the band that would later evolve into the Who. The band, called the Detours, played professional gigs from the very beginning, such as corporate and wedding functions, with Daltrey keeping a close eye on the finances as well as the music.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=31}}

Daltrey met Entwistle by chance on the street, telling him "I hear you play bass", which Entwistle subsequently said was strange "considering I was carrying one without a case!"{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=18}} In the summer of 1961, Entwistle suggested Townshend as an additional guitarist.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=18}} In the early days of the Detours, the band played instrumentals by [[the Shadows]] and [[the Ventures]], as well as a variety of pop and trad jazz covers. The line-up consisted of Daltrey as lead guitarist, Townshend on rhythm guitar, Entwistle on bass, Harry Wilson on drums and Colin Dawson as vocalist.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=19}} Daltrey was considered the leader of the group and, according to Townshend, "ran things the way he wanted them."{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=22}} Wilson was fired in the summer of 1962 in preference to [[Doug Sandom]], who despite being significantly older than the rest of the band, and married, was a more accomplished musician, having been playing semi-professionally for two years at that point.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|pp=19-20}} Dawson subsequently quit after arguing too much with Daltrey.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=22}}

With the departure of Dawson, Daltrey moved to performing as lead vocalist, and Townshend, with Entwistle's encouragement, became the sole guitarist. Through Townshend's mother, the group obtained a management contract with local promoter Robert Druce,{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=21}} who started booking the band as a support act, and they became increasingly influenced by bands they were supporting, including [[Screaming Lord Sutch]], [[Cliff Bennett]] and the Rebel Rousers, [[Shane Fenton]] and the Fentones, and [[Johnny Kidd (singer)|Johnny Kidd]] and the Pirates. The Pirates in particular became a strong influence on the group since they also only had one guitarist, [[Mick Green]]. Green inspired Townshend to take up a combined rhythm and lead guitar style, while Entwistle's bass became more of a lead instrument.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=24}} In February 1964, they became aware of the group Johnny Devlin and the Detours, so they decided to change their name.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=26}} Townshend and his room-mate Richard Barnes spent a night considering potential names, focusing on a theme of joke announcements, including "No One" and "The Group". Townshend preferred "the Hair", while Barnes liked "the Who" because it "had a pop punch".{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=65}} Daltrey listened to suggestions the next morning and decided the Who was the best choice.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=66}}

===1964–1978===

====Early career====

By the time the Detours had evolved into the Who, they had already found regular gigs including the Oldfield Hotel in Greenford, the White Hart Hotel in Acton, the Goldhawk Social Club in Shepherd's Bush, and the Notre Dame Hall in Leicester Square.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=68}} They had also replaced Druce as manager with Helmut Gorden, with whom they secured an audition with Chris Parmeinter for [[Fontana Records]].{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=70}} At the end of the audition, Parmeinter explained the drumming was a problem. Sandom claims that Townshend immediately turned on him and verbally assaulted him, threatening to fire him if his playing did not immediately improve. Sandom quit in disgust, but was persuaded to lend his kit to any potential stand-ins or replacements. Sandom and Townshend did not speak to each other again for 14 years.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=78-79}}

During a gig in late April at the Oldfield, using a stand-in drummer, the band met Moon for the first time. Unlike the other members, Moon grew up in [[Wembley]], and had been drumming in bands since 1961.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=29}} At the time he was performing with a semi-professional band called the Beachcombers, but wanted a full-time role.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=80}} Moon played a few songs with the group, breaking a bass drum pedal and tearing a drum skin in the process. The band were immediately impressed with his energy and enthusiasm, and offered him the job.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=73}} Moon performed with the Beachcombers a few more times, but eventually a clash of dates occurred and he had no option but to devote himself full-time to the Who. The Beachcombers decided to audition Sandom as a replacement, believing his clashing with the rest of the Who to be the reason he left, but were unimpressed with his playing and passed on the offer.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=80-81}}

In the summer, the Who switched management again to [[Peter Meaden]]. He decided that the group would be ideal to represent the growing [[mod (subculture)|mod]] movement in Britain which involved fashion, [[Scooter (motorcycle)|scooters]] and music genres such as [[rhythm and blues]], [[soul music|soul]], and [[beat music]]. He renamed the group the High Numbers, dressed them up in typical mod clothes,<ref name="eder">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-who-mn0000577627/biography|title=The Who&nbsp;– biography|first=Bruce|last=Eder|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=19 September 2013}}</ref> secured a second, more favourable audition with Fontana and wrote the two sides for their single "[[Zoot Suit/I'm the Face|Zoot Suit"/"I'm the Face]]" as an attempt to appeal to mods. Meaden had in fact merely written the lyrics, as the tune for "Zoot Suit" was "Misery" by the Dynamics,<ref>{{cite book|title=Icons of Rock|publisher=ABC-CLIO|page=240|isbn=978-0-3133-3845-8}}</ref> while "I'm the Face" borrowed from Slim Harpo's "[[Got Love If You Want It]]".{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=91-92}} Although Meaden attempted to promote the single, it failed to reach the top 50{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=54}} and the band reverted to calling themselves the Who.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=60}}

Meaden was replaced as manager by two filmmakers, [[Kit Lambert]] and [[Chris Stamp]]. They were looking for a young, unsigned rock group that they could make a film about,<ref name="kurutz">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/kit-lambert-mn0000080966|title=Kit Lambert&nbsp;– Biography|first=Steve|last=Kurutz|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=19 September 2013}}</ref> and had seen the band playing at the Railway Hotel in [[Wealdstone]], which had become a regular venue for them.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=55}}<ref>The Railway burned down in 2002,[http://www.carlolittle.com/hot/fire.JPG Christian Duffin: "Fire destroys the home of rock legends"], and later became blocks of flats named after members of the band.{{cite web |url= http://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=1440043 |title=Pastscape&nbsp;– Detailed Result: THE RAILWAY HOTEL  |work=pastscape.org.uk  |accessdate=25 August 2013}}</ref> Lambert found affinity with Townshend in particular, due to his art school background, and encouraged him to write songs.<ref name="kurutz"/> In August, Lambert and Stamp filmed a promotional film featuring the group and their audience at the Railway.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=56}} To highlight their music style, the band changed their set towards soul, [[rhythm and blues]] and [[Motown]] covers, and created the slogan "''Maximum R&B''".<ref name="eder"/>

In June 1964, during a performance at the Railway, Townshend accidentally broke the head of his guitar on the low ceiling above the stage.<ref name="Railway Hotel">[http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/49292974/ns/today-books/t/who-i-am-rock-icon-pete-townshend-tells-his-story/ "'Who I Am': Rock icon Pete Townshend tells his story"]. MSNBC. Retrieved 23 November 2012</ref> Angered by laughing from the audience, he smashed the instrument on the stage, then picked up another guitar and continued the show. The following week, the audience were keen to see a repeat of the event. Moon promptly obliged and kicked his drum kit over.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=125}} Subsequent [[auto-destructive art]], as described by Townshend, became a feature of the Who's live set.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=126}}<ref name="RS 29">{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5939229/29_the_who/|title=The Greatest Artists of All Time: The Who|last=Vedder|first=Eddie|date=15 April 2004|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=16 May 2008}}</ref> The incident at the Railway Hotel is one of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's "50 Moments That Changed the History of Rock 'n' Roll".<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/6085455/the_moments |title=50 Moments That Changed the History of Rock 'n' Roll |work=Rolling Stone |date=24 June 2004 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20090101091918/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/6085455/the_moments/ |archivedate=1 January 2009}}</ref>

====First singles and ''My Generation''====

By late 1964, the Who had started to become popular in London's [[The Marquee|Marquee]] club and a rave review of their live act appeared in ''[[Melody Maker]]''.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=134}} Lambert and Stamp had managed to attract the attention of the American producer [[Shel Talmy]], who had already found success by producing [[the Kinks]]. Townshend had written a song, "[[I Can't Explain]]", that deliberately sounded like the Kinks to attract Talmy's attention. Talmy saw the group in rehearsals and was immediately impressed. He signed the group to his production company,{{sfn|Howard|2004|pp=106-107}} and sold the recording to the US arm of [[Decca Records]], which meant that the group's early singles were released in Britain on [[Brunswick Records]], one of UK Decca's labels for US artists.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=151-152}}

The Who achieved a major boost in popularity when they appeared on the television programme ''[[Ready Steady Go!]]''<ref name="eder"/> Lambert and Stamp had been given the task of finding "typical teens", and simply invited the group's regular audience from the Goldhawk Social Club.<ref name="carr">{{cite AV media notes|title=The Kids are Alright (soundtrack)|publisher=Polydor|year=1979|first=Roy|last=Carr}}</ref> Their enthusiastic reception on television, aided by regular airplay on [[pirate radio]] stations such as [[Radio Caroline]],{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=152}} helped the single slowly climb the charts during early 1965, eventually reaching the top 10.<ref name="Roberts"/> For the follow-up single, "[[Anyway, Anyhow, Anywhere]]", credited to both Townshend and Daltrey,<ref name="Roberts"/> Talmy arranged the deliberate use of guitar [[audio feedback|feedback]], which was so unconventional that the US arm of Decca rejected the master tapes. The single also reached the top 10 in the UK.{{sfn|Howard|2004|pp=107-108}}

The transition into a hit-making band with original material, eagerly encouraged by Lambert, did not sit well with Daltrey, particularly after a session of recording R&B covers for an album was shelved.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=121}} The Who were not particularly good friends either, with the notable exception of Moon and Entwistle, who enjoyed clubbing together.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=126}} The group experienced a particularly fraught time when touring Denmark in September, which culminated in Daltrey throwing Moon's [[amphetamine]]s down the toilet and physically assaulting him. Immediately on returning to Britain, Daltrey was sacked from the Who.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=93}} After a band meeting, he was reinstated on the strict condition that the group became a democracy without his dominant leadership. At the same time, the group enlisted [[Richard Cole]] as a roadie.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|pp=130-132}}

The group recorded a follow-up single, "[[My Generation]]", in October. Townshend had written it as a slow blues, but after several abortive attempts, it was turned into a more powerful song with a bass solo from Entwistle.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=182}} It became the highest charting single the group have achieved to date, reaching number 2.<ref name="charlesworth">{{cite AV media notes |title=Live At Leeds (1995 CD reissue)|others=The Who|year=1995|first=Chris|last=Charlesworth|type=CD|publisher=[[Polydor]]|id=527-169-2|location=UK}}</ref>{{rp|12}} The debut album ''[[My Generation (album)|My Generation]]'' (''The Who Sings My Generation'' in the US) was released in late 1965. It included original material written by Townshend, including the title track and "[[The Kids Are Alright (song)|The Kids Are Alright]]", as well as several [[James Brown]] covers that Daltrey favoured, from the aborted session earlier that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-who-sings-my-generation-mw0000020578|title=My Generation&nbsp;– review|first=Richie|last=Unterberger|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=19 September 2013}}</ref>

After ''My Generation'', the Who fell out with Talmy, which meant an abrupt end to their recording contract. Lambert and Stamp claimed the royalty rate was poor,{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=199}} while Talmy claimed it was due to Lambert wanting to take control of the recordings away from him. The resulting legal acrimony resulted in Talmy holding the rights to the master tapes, which prevented the album from being reissued. The dispute was finally resolved in 2002, when it saw a proper remix and CD reissue.{{sfn|Howard|2004|p=108}}  Meanwhile, the Who were signed to [[Robert Stigwood]]'s Reaction Label, releasing "[[Substitute (The Who song)|Substitute]]". Talmy took legal action over the B-side, "Instant Party", and so the single was withdrawn and replaced with "Waltz for a Pig", recorded by the [[Graham Bond|Graham Bond Organisation]] under the pseudonym "the Who Orchestra".{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=203}}

Subsequent singles released in 1966 included "[[I'm a Boy]]", about a boy dressed as a girl, taken from an abortive collection of songs called "Quads",{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=217}} "[[Happy Jack (song)|Happy Jack]]",{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=109}} and an EP, ''[[Ready Steady Who]]'', that tied in with their regular appearances on ''Ready Steady Go!''{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=218}}

====''A Quick One'' and ''The Who Sell Out''====
[[File:Roger Daltrey -left and Keith Moon-right 1967.jpg|thumb|left|Roger Daltrey and Keith Moon, 1967]]

To alleviate some of the financial pressure on the band, Lambert arranged a songwriting deal which required each member to write two songs for the next album. Entwistle contributed "[[Boris the Spider]]" and "Whiskey Man" and found a niche role as second songwriter,{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=225}} but after recording the material, they found they needed to fill an extra ten minutes. Lambert encouraged Townshend to write a longer piece, which became "[[A Quick One, While He's Away]]". The album was subsequently titled ''[[A Quick One]]''{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=227}} (released as ''Happy Jack'' in the US),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/a-quick-one-happy-jack-mw0000197244|title=A Quick One (Happy Jack)|first=Ritchie|last=Unterberger|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=24 September 2013}}</ref> and reached number 4 in the charts.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=229}} It was followed in 1967 by the UK Top 5 single "[[Pictures of Lily]]."{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=420}}

By 1966, ''Ready Steady Go!'' had stopped being broadcast, and mod was no longer as popular. The Who found themselves in competition with [[Cream (band)|Cream]] and [[the Jimi Hendrix Experience]] on the London gigging circuit.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|po=239-240}} Lambert and Stamp realised that commercial success in the US was paramount to the group's future, and so arranged a deal with promoter [[Frank Barsalona]] for a short package tour in New York.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=243}} The group's performances, which still involved smashing guitars and kicking over drums, were well received,{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=247}} and led to them being on the bill at the [[Monterey Pop Festival]], which was their first major appearance in the US. Immediately afterwards, the group toured the country with [[Herman's Hermits]].{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=189}} Moon by this point had also attracted a reputation of destroying hotel rooms while on tour,{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=247}} with a particular interest in explosions, which was evident when the group appeared on ''[[The Smothers Brothers Comedy Hour]]'' where he detonated his drum kit.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=276}}

The next album was ''[[The Who Sell Out]]''—a [[concept album]] based on pirate radio, which had been instrumental in raising the Who's popularity, but had been banned that August. It included several humorous jingles and mock commercials between songs,{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=148-149}} a mini rock opera called "Rael" whose closing theme ended up on ''[[Tommy (album)|Tommy]]'', and the Who's biggest US single, "[[I Can See for Miles]]".{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=149}} Later that year, Lambert and Stamp formed their own record label, [[Track Records]], with distribution by [[Polydor]]. As well as signing Hendrix, Track became the imprint used for all the Who's UK output until the mid-1970s.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=250}}

The group started 1968 with a fairly disastrous tour of Australia and New Zealand with the [[Small Faces]],{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=196}} where the ''New Zealand Truth'' called them "unwashed, foul-smelling, booze-swilling no-hopers",{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=293}} and continued to tour across the US and Canada during the spring and summer.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=190}}

====''Tommy'', Woodstock and ''Live at Leeds''====
By 1968, the Who had started to attract attention in the [[underground press]].{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=191}} Townshend had stopped using drugs by this point, and became interested in the teachings of [[Meher Baba]].{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=294}} In August, he gave a major interview to ''Rolling Stone'' editor [[Jann Wenner]] in which he described an album project he was working on, describing the plot of what eventually became the ''[[Tommy (rock opera)|Tommy]]'' album in intricate detail. The basic concept was to describe the life of a deaf, dumb and blind boy, and his attempt to communicate with others.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|pp=314-315}}<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20090401071039/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/petetownshend/articles/story/9306658/the_rolling_stone_interview_pete_townshend |title=The Rolling Stone Interview: Pete Townshend |date=28 September 1968 |first=Jann|last=Wenner|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20090401071039/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/petetownshend/articles/story/9306658/the_rolling_stone_interview_pete_townshend |archivedate = 1 April 2009}}</ref> Some songs, such as "Welcome" and "Amazing Journey" came directly from Townshend's studies of Baba,{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=320}} while others came from observations within the band. "Sally Simpson" was written about a fan trying to climb onstage at a gig by [[the Doors]] that they attended{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=316}} and "Pinball Wizard" was written to attract the interest of ''New York Times'' journalist Nik Cohn.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=221}} Townshend later said "I wanted the story of ''Tommy'' to have several levels&nbsp;... a rock singles level and a bigger concept level", containing the spiritual message he wanted as well as being entertaining.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=318}}

By the end of the year, 18 months of continuous touring had led to a well rehearsed and tight live band, which was evident when they performed "A Quick One While He's Away" at ''[[The Rolling Stones Rock and Roll Circus]]'', a planned television special. The Stones considered their own performance lacklustre, and the project was shelved and never broadcast.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=228-29}} However, the Who had not released an album in over a year, and had not completed the recording of ''Tommy'', which continued well into 1969.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=324}} Lambert was a key figure in keeping the group focused and the album completed, and typed up a script to help them understand the storyline and how the songs fitted together.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=220}}

The album was eventually completed and released in May with the accompanying single, "[[Pinball Wizard]]", and a debut performance at [[Ronnie Scott's]],{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=222}} after which the group set out on tour, playing most of the new album live.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=326}} The album was an immediate success, selling 200,000 copies in the first two weeks of release in the US.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=223}} In addition to commercial success, ''Tommy'' became a critical smash, ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' saying, "...&nbsp;for sheer power, invention and brilliance of performance, ''Tommy'' outstrips anything which has ever come out of a recording studio",<ref name="Sanctuary">[http://web.archive.org/web/20070928010522/http://www.sanctuarygroup.com/index.php?page=1&l1=6&l2=10&l3=0&getArticleId=466 The Who]. Sanctuary Group, Artist Management. Retrieved 3 January 2007.</ref> and ''[[Melody Maker]]'' declaring: "Surely the Who are now the band against which all others are to be judged."<ref name="The Who Kennedy Center">{{cite web|url=http://www.kennedy-center.org/calendar/index.cfm?fuseaction=showIndividual&entity_id=20531&source_type=A |title=The Who Kennedy Center Honors|publisher=The Kennedy Center|accessdate=24 November 2010}}</ref> Daltrey's singing had become significantly better, and it translated well into performing the new material. He had grown his hair and tended to wear open shirts on stage, and this set the template for rock singers in the 1970s.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=344}} Townshend, meanwhile, had taken to wearing a [[boiler suit]] and [[Dr. Martens|Doctor Martens]] on stage,{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=344}} and settled on the [[Gibson SG Special]] as his main live instrument, using one for every gig until 1973. Today, Gibson manufacture a signature Pete Townshend SG.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.gibson.com/Products/Electric-Guitars/SG/Gibson-USA/50th-Anniversary-Pete-Townshend-SG.aspx|title=50th Anniversary Pete Townshend SG|publisher=[[Gibson Guitar Corporation|Gibson]]|accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref>

In August, the Who performed at the [[Woodstock Festival]], despite being reluctant to do so and only agreeing after being paid $13,000 up front.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=240}} Originally scheduled to appear at 10pm on Saturday, 16 August,{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=237}} the festival ran late and the group did not take to the stage until 5am on Sunday,{{sfn|Evans|Kingsbury|2009|p=165}} where they played most of ''Tommy''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Spitz|first=Bob|year=1979|title=Barefoot in Babylon: The Creation of the Woodstock Music Festival|publisher=W.W. Norton & Company|page=462|isbn=0-393-30644-5}}</ref> During their performance, [[Youth International Party|Yippie]] leader [[Abbie Hoffman]] interrupted the set to give a political speech about the arrest of [[John Sinclair (poet)|John Sinclair]], before being kicked offstage by Townshend{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=240}} (who infamously shouted "Fuck off my fucking stage!").{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=224}}{{sfn|Evans|Kingsbury|2009|p=165}} During "[[See Me, Feel Me]]", the sun rose almost as if on cue{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=241}} (Entwistle later said "God was our lighting man"),{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=224}} while at the very end of the set, Townshend threw his guitar into the audience.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=241}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/28847236/the_road_to_woodstock_the_stories_behind_rock_history/11 |title=The Who Cement Their Place in Rock History |work=Rolling Stone |date=25 June 2009 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20090628010821/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/28847236/the_road_to_woodstock_the_stories_behind_rock_history/11 |archivedate=28 June 2009 |deadurl=yes}}</ref> The set was professionally recorded and filmed, and portions of it appeared on [[Woodstock (film)|the ''Woodstock'' film]], ''[[The Old Grey Whistle Test]]'' and ''The Kids Are Alright''.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=238}}

While Woodstock in general has been regarded as culturally significant, the Who have been critical of the event. Roadie John "Wiggie" Wolff, who arranged the band's payment, described the event as "a shambles",{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=237}} while Daltrey declared it as "the worst gig we ever played"{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=350}} and Townshend said, "I thought the whole of America had gone mad."{{sfn|Evans|Kingsbury|2009|p=165}} A more favourable appearance came a few weeks later at the second [[Isle of Wight Festival]], which Townshend later described as "a great concert for us".{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=240}}

By 1970, the Who were widely considered to be one of the best and most popular live rock bands, with [[Chris Charlesworth]] describing concerts as "leading to a kind of rock nirvana that most bands can only dream about".<ref name="charlesworth"/>{{rp|5}} They decided a live album would help demonstrate the contrast of their gigs to the studio work on ''Tommy'', and set about listening to the hours of recordings they had accumulated. Townshend baulked at the prospect of doing so, and insisted that all the tapes should be burned. Instead, they booked two shows, one in Leeds on 14 February, and one in Hull the following day, with the specific intention of recording them for a live album. Technical problems from the Hull gig resulted in the Leeds gig being used, which became ''[[Live at Leeds]]''.<ref name="charlesworth"/>{{rp|5}} The album is viewed by several critics as being one of the best live rock albums of all time, including ''[[The Independent]]'',<ref name="Best Live Album">{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/shake-rattle-and-roll-the-best-live-albums-of-all-time-2131327.html |title=Shake, rattle and roll!: The best live albums of all time |newspaper=The Independent |date=12 November 2010 |accessdate=22 November 2012}}</ref><ref name="Independent">{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/live-at-leeds-whos-best-481358.html |title=Live at Leeds: Who's best&nbsp;... |newspaper=The Independent |date=7 June 2006 |accessdate=3 January 2007}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]''<ref name="Telegraph">{{cite news |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandjazzmusic/3653281/Hope-I-dont-have-a-heart-attack.html |title=Hope I don't have a heart attack |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=22 June 2006 |accessdate=3 January 2007}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone''<ref name="RollingStoneLiveatLeeds">{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/6599133/170_live_at_leeds/|title=Live at Leeds|work=Rolling Stone|date=1 November 2003|accessdate=24 June 2008}}</ref> and the ''[[BBC]]''.<ref name="BBCLiveatLeeds">{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/leeds/content/articles/2005/09/02/music_the_who_live_in_leeds_feature.shtml |title=The Who: Live at Leeds |publisher=BBC |date=18 August 2006 |accessdate=3 January 2007}}</ref> The original album contained six songs, taken from the middle and end of the set, and has been reissued several times in expanded and [[remaster]]ed versions, which remedy technical problems and contain the performance of ''Tommy'', as well as renditions of earlier singles.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=426}}

The Leeds University gig was part of the ''Tommy'' tour, which not only included shows in European [[opera house]]s but saw the Who become the first rock act to play at the [[Metropolitan Opera|Metropolitan Opera House]] in New York City.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=352}} In March the Who released the UK top twenty hit "[[The Seeker (The Who song)|The Seeker]]", continuing a theme of issuing singles separate to albums.<ref name="Roberts"/>

====''Lifehouse'' and ''Who's Next''====
The success of ''Tommy'' secured the Who's future, and made them millionaires. The group reacted in different ways—Daltrey and Entwistle lived comfortably, Townshend was embarrassed at his wealth, which he felt at odds with Meher Baba's ideals, while Moon spent frivously.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=354}} Entwistle, tired of not getting enough of his own songs on Who albums, recorded ''[[Smash Your Head Against the Wall]]'', his first solo effort.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=364}}

During the latter part of 1970, Townshend thought of a suitable follow-up to ''Tommy''. He came up with ''[[Lifehouse (rock opera)|Lifehouse]]'', which was designed to be a multi-media project symbolising the relationship between an artist and his audience.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=368-369}} He developed numerous ideas in his home studio, creating various layers of [[synthesizer]]s,{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=373}} and the [[Young Vic]] theatre in London was booked for a series of experimental concerts. Townshend approached the gigs with optimism; the rest of the band were just happy to be gigging again.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=375}} Eventually, the others confronted Townshend, complaining the project was too complicated and they should simply record another album. Things deteriorated to the point at which Townshend had a nervous breakdown, and ''Lifehouse'' was abandoned.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=378}}<ref name="whosnext">{{cite AV media notes |title=Who's Next |others=The Who |year=1995, 1971 |first=Pete |last=Townshend |authorlink=Pete Townshend |pages=3–7 |type=CD liner |publisher=MCA Records |id=MCAD-11269 }}</ref>

[[File:The Who at Charlotte, NC (1971).jpg|thumb|270px|The Who at the Coliseum, Charlotte, North Carolina, 20 November 1971{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=294}}]]

In March 1971, the Who began recording the available ''Lifehouse'' material with [[Kit Lambert]] in [[New York]], which had to be abandoned due to Lambert's increasing dependency on [[heroin]],<ref name="whosnext"/> and then restarted the sessions with [[Glyn Johns]] in April. Selections from the material, with one unrelated song ("[[My Wife]]") by Entwistle, were released as a traditional studio album, ''[[Who's Next]]''. The album became their most successful among critics and fans, reaching No.&nbsp;4 in the US pop charts and No.&nbsp;1 in the UK. Two tracks from the album, "[[Baba O'Riley]]" and "[[Won't Get Fooled Again]]", are early examples of synthesizer use in rock music; both tracks' keyboard sounds were generated in real time by a [[Lowrey organ]], and on "Won't Get Fooled Again", it was further processed through a [[VCS3]] synthesizer.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=275}}
Townshend was credited with "VCS3 Organ" and "ARP Synthesizer" on the final album credits. "Baba O'Riley" also featured a violin solo by [[Dave Arbus]], produced by Moon.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Who's Next|others=The Who|publisher=Track Records|id=2408 102|year=1971}}</ref>

The Who continued to issue ''Lifehouse''-related material over the next few years. In October 1971 they released the UK top twenty hit "[[Let's See Action]]", which came from the project, followed by further singles "[[Join Together (song)|Join Together]]" and "[[Relay (song)|Relay]]".<ref name="Roberts">Roberts, David (2006). ''[[British Hit Singles & Albums]]''. London: Guinness World Records Limited</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Pete Townshend: the minstrel's dilemma|first=Larry|last=Smith|publisher=Praeger Frederick A|year=1999|isbn=978-0-275-96472-6|page=171}}</ref><ref name="Whitburn">[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]] (2006). ''The [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] Book of Top 40 Hits''. Billboard Books</ref>

Following the success of ''Who's Next'', the band went back on tour, replacing much of the old ''Tommy'' material with the new songs.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=277}} On 4 November they opened the Rainbow Theatre in London and played for three nights,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theatrestrust.org.uk/resources/theatres/show/2301-new-rainbow-astoria|title=New Rainbow/Astoria|publisher=The Theatres Trust|accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref> continuing on to the US later that month. Robert Hilburn of ''The Los Angeles Times'' described the Who as "the Greatest Show on Earth".{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=278}} The tour was slightly disrupted at the Civic Auditorium in San Francisco on 12 December, when Moon passed out over his kit after an overdose of brandy and barbiturates.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=295}} He recovered and completed the gig, playing to his usual strength.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=301}}

====''Quadrophenia'', ''Tommy'' film and ''The Who by Numbers''====
[[File:The Who Hamburg 1972 2.jpg|thumb|upright|The Who at the Ernst-Mercke-Halle, Hamburg, 12 August 1972{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=307}}]]

Following the tour for ''Who's Next'', and needing time to write a follow-up, Townshend insisted that the Who take a lengthy break. Having been continually touring since the band started, there was no group activity for the first part of 1972.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=302}} They then started recording new material, but the results were uninspired, and the sessions were abandoned. Tensions began to emerge between the group members—Townshend believed Daltrey just wanted a money-making band; Daltrey, conversely, thought Townshend's projects were getting pretentious. In addition, Moon's behaviour was becoming increasingly destructive and problematic.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=390-91}} Daltrey had also discovered that Lambert and Stamp had left significant amounts of money unaccounted for, and believed them to be no longer effective as managers, which Townshend and Moon disputed.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=406}} Following a short [[The Who Tour 1972|European tour]], the remainder of 1972 was spent working on an orchestral version of ''Tommy'', with Daltrey and Townshend collaborating with [[Lou Reizner]].{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=401}}

By 1973, the Who had decided to record an album about mod and its subculture, set against clashes with [[Rockers (youth movement)|Rockers]] in the early 1960s in the UK, particularly at [[Brighton]], called ''[[Quadrophenia]]''.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=412-413}} The story is about a boy named Jimmy, who undergoes a personality crisis, and his relationship with his family and the mod culture.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=341,344}} By the time the album was being recorded, relationships between the band and Lambert and Stamp had broken down irreparably, and [[Bill Curbishley]] replaced them as manager.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=412}} Townshend played a variety of multi-tracked synthesizers, and Entwistle played several overdubbed horn parts.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=414}} The album became their highest charting cross-Atlantic success, peaking at No.&nbsp;2 in the UK and US.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=428}}

The tour for the album started in [[Stoke on Trent]] in October,{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|pp=335-336}} but was immediately beset with problems. Having successfully played "Baba O'Riley" and "Won't Get Fooled Again" to a backing tape with the synthesizer parts live, Townshend had assembled a variety of similar tapes for ''Quadrophenia'' for the band to play along to. Unfortunately, the technology was not sophisticated enough to deal with the demands of the music, and rehearsals were interrupted due to an argument which culminated in Daltrey punching Townshend and knocking him out cold.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=359}} At a gig in Newcastle, the tapes completely malfunctioned, and an enraged Townshend physically dragged soundman [[Bob Pridden]] onstage, screamed verbal abuse at him, kicked all the amps over and partially destroyed the backing tapes. The show was abandoned in place of an "oldies" set, at the end of which Townshend smashed his guitar and Moon kicked over his drumkit.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=336}}{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=359}} The US tour started on 20 November at the [[Cow Palace]], [[Daly City, California]], where Moon passed out during "Won't Get Fooled Again" and, after a break backstage, again in "[[Magic Bus (song)|Magic Bus]]". Townshend asked the audience, "Can anyone play the drums?—I mean somebody good." An audience member, [[Scot Halpin]], filled in for the rest of the show.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=337}} After a show in [[Montreal]], the band (except for Daltrey, who retired to bed early) caused so much destruction to their hotel room, that the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police|Canadian Mounted Police]] were called, and they were arrested.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=363}}

[[File:The Who (1974).png|left|thumb|The Who in 1974]]
By 1974, work had begun in earnest on [[Tommy (1975 film)|the ''Tommy'' film]]. [[Ken Russell]] was suggested as director by Stigwood, and Townshend had admired his previous work.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=437}} The film featured a star-studded cast, including the band members themselves. After auditioning [[David Essex]] for the title role, the part went to Daltrey, following some persuasion from the band.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=439}} The other cast members included [[Ann-Margret]], [[Oliver Reed]], [[Eric Clapton]], [[Tina Turner]], [[Elton John]] and [[Jack Nicholson]].{{sfn|Marsh|1983|pp=439-440}} Townshend and Entwistle worked on the film soundtrack for most of the year, but because Moon had moved to [[Los Angeles]], they decided to use [[Kenney Jones]] and [[Tony Newman (drummer)|Tony Newman]] as drummers. A number of session men also played bass and keyboards. Elton John insisted on using his own band for his performance of "Pinball Wizard".{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=441}}

The film premiered on 18 March 1975, to a standing ovation from the audience.{{sfn|Neil|Kent|2009|p=369}} Ann-Margret received a [[Golden Globe Award]] for her performance, and was also nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The American Film Institute desk reference|page=128|year=2002|isbn=978-0-7894-8934-0|publisher=DK|editor1-first=Melinda|editor1-last=Corey}}</ref> Townshend was also nominated for an Oscar for his work in scoring and adapting the music for the film.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=451}} ''Tommy'' was shown at the [[1975 Cannes Film Festival]], but was not entered into the main competition.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|pp=371-372}} It won the award for Rock Movie of the Year in the First Annual [[Rock Music Awards]].{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=373}} It was a commercial success, generating over $2M in box-office receipts in the first month of release.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=369}} The soundtrack was also successful, reaching number 2 on the ''Billboard'' albums chart.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=430}}

[[File:Keith Moon 4 - The Who - 1975.jpg|thumb|Moon in 1975]]

Because work on ''Tommy'' took up most of 1974, live performances by the Who were restricted to a one-off show at Charlton Athletic Football Ground in May in front of 80,000 fans{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=351}} and a few dates at Madison Square Garden in June.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=354}} Towards the end of the year, the group released the [[outtakes]] album ''[[Odds & Sods]]'', which featured several songs from the aborted ''Lifehouse'' project that had been compiled by Entwistle.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=446}}

Their 1975 album, ''[[The Who by Numbers]]'', had introspective songs that dealt with disillusionment, lightened by "[[Squeeze Box (The Who song)|Squeeze Box]]", another hit single.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=364}} The group set out on tour in October, playing little new material, removing most of the ''Quadrophenia'' numbers and reintroducing ''Tommy'' to the set.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=365}} On 6 December 1975, the Who set the record for largest indoor concert at the [[Pontiac Silverdome]], attended by 78,000 fans.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=443}} On 31 May 1976, they played at [[The Valley (London)|the Valley]], the home of Charlton Athletic, in what was listed for more than ten years in the [[Guinness Book of Records]] as the world's loudest concert, at over 120 dB.<ref name="Sanctuary"/> Entwistle considered the Who's live performances to be at their peak at this time.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=465}}

====''Who Are You'' and Moon's death====
[[File:Daltrey and Townshend.jpg|thumb|left|Daltrey and Townshend, 21 October 1976, Maple Leaf Gardens, Toronto, Ontario—their last ever public gig with Moon]]

Following the end of the 1976 tour, Townshend insisted on having most of the following year off to spend time with his family.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=394}} Halfway through the year, he discovered that [[Allen Klein]] had managed to buy a stake in his publishing company. A settlement was reached, but, feeling upset and disillusioned, he went to the [[Speakeasy]] where he bumped into [[the Sex Pistols]]' Steve Jones and Paul Cook, who were fans of the Who. After leaving the club, he passed out in a doorway, where a policeman claimed he would not be arrested if he could stand and walk. The events inspired the title track of the next album, ''[[Who Are You]]''.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=396}}

The group reconvened in September 1977, when Townshend announced there would be no live performances for the immediate future, a decision that Daltrey endorsed. By this point, Moon was so out of shape that the Who conceded it would be difficult for him to cope with touring. The only live gig performed that year was an informal show at the [[Gaumont State Cinema]] in [[Kilburn, London|Kilburn]], London, on 15 December, as part of an upcoming documentary film about the band, ''[[The Kids Are Alright (film)|The Kids Are Alright]]''.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=406}} Having not played for 14 months, the band was weak. Moon's playing was particularly lacklustre and he had gained a lot of weight. Further filming was shelved.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=494}}

Recording of ''Who Are You'' started in January 1978. Daltrey clashed with Johns over the production of his vocals, and Moon's drumming was so poor that Daltrey and Entwistle considered he should be sacked. His playing subsequently improved, but on one track, "Music Must Change", he was absent entirely.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=496}} In May, the Who were required to film another performance at Shepperton Sound Studios in May for ''The Kids Are Alright'', due to the poor performance at Kilburn. Their performance was strong, and several tracks were used on the final cut. It was the last gig Moon ever performed with the Who.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=499}}

The album was released on 18 August, and became their biggest and fastest seller to that date, peaking at No.&nbsp;6 in the UK and No.&nbsp;2 in the US.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=430}} Instead of touring, Daltrey, Townshend and Moon did a series of promotional television interviews, while Entwistle worked on the soundtrack for ''The Kids Are Alright''.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=504-505}}

On 6 September, Moon attended a party held by [[Paul McCartney]] to celebrate [[Buddy Holly]]'s birthday. Upon arriving back at his flat, he took 32 tablets of [[Heminevrin]]—a drug prescribed to combat his [[alcohol withdrawal]].{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=416}} He passed out the following morning, and was discovered dead later that day.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|pp=506-507}} He was 32.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=416}}

===1978–1983===
The day after Moon's death, Townshend issued a statement saying "We are more determined than ever to carry on, and we want the spirit of the group to which Keith contributed so much to go on, although no human being can ever take his place".{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=416}} In November 1978, [[Kenney Jones]], formerly of the [[Small Faces]] and the [[Faces (band)|Faces]], joined the band as Moon's successor.{{sfn|Townshend|2012|p=287}} Keyboardist [[John Bundrick|John "Rabbit" Bundrick]] also joined the live band as an unofficial member.{{sfn|Townshend|2012|p=289}}
Bundrick had been scheduled to play on ''Who Are You'', but he was unavailable due to an injury.{{sfn|Townshend|2012|p=264}}

On 2 May 1979, the Who returned to the stage with a well-received concert at the [[Rainbow Theatre]] in London, followed up over the spring and summer by performances at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] in France,{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=509}} in Scotland, at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] in London, in West Germany, at the [[Capitol Theatre (Passaic)|Capitol Theater]] in Passaic, New Jersey, and in five dates at [[Madison Square Garden]] in New York City.<ref name="official"/>

That year also saw the release of [[Quadrophenia (film)|a film of ''Quadrophenia'']]. It was directed by [[Franc Roddam]] in his feature-directing début,{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=518}} and features straightforward acting rather than the musical numbers in ''Tommy''. [[Sting (musician)|Sting]] starred as the Ace Face, a fellow mod and friend of Jimmy. The idea of casting [[John Lydon]] as Jimmy was considered, but the role eventually went to [[Phil Daniels]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/26/movies/quadrophenia-reissue-new-spark-for-enduring-mods.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title='Quadrophenia,' Still a Flash Point for the Mods|first=Marc|last=Spitz|work=The New York Times|date=24 August 2012|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> The soundtrack is notable for being Jones' first appearance on record after taking over as full-time drummer from Moon after his death, performing on newly written material that was not on the original album.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/kenny-jones-joins-the-who-19781228|title=Kenny Jones Joins The Who|first=Salley|last=Rayl|first2=James|last2=Henke}}</ref> The film was a critical and box office success in the UK{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=535}} and appealed to the growing [[mod revival]] movement. [[The Jam]] were noted for being musically influenced by the Who, particularly through the relationship between Townshend and their leader, [[Paul Weller]].{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=510}}

''The Kids Are Alright'' was also completed in 1979. It was a retrospective of the band's career to that date, directed by Jeff Stein.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=486}} The film included footage of the band at Monterey, Woodstock and Pontiac, and clips from the Smothers Brothers' show and ''[[Russell Harty|Russell Harty Plus]]''.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=486}} The film became significant for the Who, since Moon died only one week after he had seen the rough cut of the film with Daltrey. It contains Moon's final live performance at [[Shepperton Studios]],{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=503}} and an audio track of him playing drum sounds over silent footage of himself was the last time he ever played the drums.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=514}}

In December, the Who became the third band, after the Beatles and [[the Band]], to be featured on the cover of ''Time''. The article, written by [[Jay Cocks]], said the band had "outpaced, outlasted, outlived and outclassed" all of their rock band contemporaries.<ref name="Time Magazine">{{cite news|last=Cocks |first=Jay |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,920745,00.html |title=Rock's Outer Limits |work=Time |date=17 December 1979 |accessdate=24 November 2010}}</ref>

====Cincinnati tragedy====

{{main|1979 The Who concert disaster}}
On 3 December 1979, a [[The Who Tour 1979|short tour of the United States]] was marred by [[Tragedy (event)|tragedy]] in [[Cincinnati|Cincinnati, Ohio]], where a crowd crush at the [[U.S. Bank Arena|Riverfront Coliseum]] killed 11 fans.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/rock-and-roll-tragedy-why-eleven-died-at-the-whos-cincinnati-concert-19800124|title=Rock and Roll Tragedy : Why Eleven Died at The Who's Cincinnati Concert|first=Chet|last=Flippo|work=Rolling Stone|date=24 January 1980|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> This was due in part to the use of [[festival seating]]—a seating arrangement in which seating is unassigned (non-reserved), so the first to enter the venue get the best positions to view the concert. Additionally, many fans waiting outside mistook the band's [[sound check]] for the actual concert, and attempted to force their way inside. When only a small number of the arena's entrance doors were opened, a bottleneck situation ensued and, with so many thousands trying to gain entry, the crush became deadly.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=512}}

The Who were not told until after the show because civic authorities feared crowd problems if the concert was cancelled. The band were deeply shaken upon learning of the incident, and requested that appropriate safety precautions be taken at subsequent concerts.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=513}} The following evening, in [[Buffalo, New York]], Daltrey told the crowd that the band had "lost a lot of family last night and this show's for them."<ref>{{cite journal|title= |work=Time|volume=114|issue=19–27|page=225}}</ref>

====Change and break-up====
[[File:BouncingTownshend.jpg|thumb|left|The Who in Toronto, 1980]]

Daltrey took a short break from the Who in 1980 to work on the film ''[[McVicar (film)|McVicar]]'', in which he took the lead role of bank robber [[John McVicar]].{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=492}} The [[McVicar (album)|soundtrack album]] is a Daltrey solo album featuring other members of the Who, and was his most successful solo release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/mcvicar-mw0000184114|title=McVicar&nbsp;– Roger Daltrey|first=William|last=Ruhlmann|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref>

The Who released two studio albums with Jones as drummer, ''[[Face Dances]]'' (1981) and ''[[It's Hard]]'' (1982). ''Face Dances'' produced a US top twenty and UK top ten hit with the single "[[You Better You Bet]]" and its video was shown on [[MTV]] on its first day of airing.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/?id=2mDnc4apw_0C&pg=PA33&dq=%22the+who%22+MTV+%22you+better+you+bet%22+1981#v=onepage&q=%22the%20who%22%20MTV%20%22you%20better%20you%20bet%22%201981&f=false|title=Remember the 80s: Now That's What I Call Nostalgia!|first=Richard|last=Evans|publisher=Anova Books|page=33|isbn=978-1-906032-12-8|year=2008}}</ref> Both ''Face Dances'' and ''It's Hard'' sold fairly well and the latter received a five-star review in ''Rolling Stone''.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/its-hard-19820930|first=Parke|last=Puterbaugh|title=It's Hard|work=Rolling Stone|date=30 September 1982|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> "[[Eminence Front]]" was a hit, and became a regular feature of live shows, including future reunions.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/readers-poll-the-whos-10-greatest-songs-20121017/8-eminence-front-0185516|title=Readers' Poll: The Who's 10 Greatest Songs : 8 'Eminence Front'|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref>

By this time, however, Townshend had fallen into a depression, realising his role as a visionary had come to an end.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=514}} He was again at odds with Daltrey and Entwistle, who merely wanted to tour and play hits. In addition, Jones' consistent and precise drumming was very different from Moon's wild and unpredictable playing.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|pp=517-518}} There was resentment, too, that Townshend appeared to have saved his best songs for his solo album, ''[[Empty Glass]]''.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=519}} He briefly became addicted to heroin, before cleaning up at Meg Patterson's San Diego clinic in early 1982.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=523}}

[[File:John Entwisle 1987.jpg|right|thumb|John Entwistle performing with The Who at the Manchester Apollo, 1981]]

Townshend wanted to stop touring completely and for the Who to become solely a studio act, though Entwistle threatened to quit unless there were promises of further tours.<ref name="greene82"/> Townshend did not change his mind, and so the Who embarked on their "farewell" tour of the US and Canada<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-25-boldest-career-moves-in-rock-history-20110318/pete-townshend-becomes-a-book-editor-20110323|title=The 25 Boldest Career Moves in Rock History: Pete Townshend Becomes a Book Editor|work=Rolling Stone|date=23 March 2011|accessdate=22 November 2012}}</ref> with [[the Clash]] as support, including two shows at [[Shea Stadium]] in New York<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/earshot/clash-unveils-12-disc-set-633476|title=The Clash Unveils 12-Disc Set|first=Mitch|last=Myers|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=21 September 2013|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> and ending in Toronto on 17 December.<ref name="greene82">{{cite journal|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/flashback-the-who-wrap-up-their-farewell-tour-in-1982-20130613|title=Flashback: The Who Wrap Up Their 'Farewell' Tour in 1982|first=Andy|last=Greene|date=13 June 2013|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref>

Townshend spent part of 1983 trying to write material for the studio album still owed to [[Warner Bros. Records]] from a contract in 1980.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=524}} By the end of 1983, however, Townshend declared himself unable to generate material appropriate for the Who and paid for himself and Jones to be released from the record contract.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=538}} He then focused on solo projects such as ''[[White City: A Novel]]'', ''[[The Iron Man: A Musical|The Iron Man]]'' (which featured Daltrey and Entwistle and two songs on the album credited to "the Who"), and ''[[Psychoderelict]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/pete-townshend-mn0000842351/discography|title=Pete Townshend discography|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=25 September 2013}}</ref>

===Reunions===
In July 1985, the Who re-formed for a one-off performance at [[Bob Geldof|Bob Geldof's]] [[Live Aid]] concert at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]], London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1643506/looking-back-at-live-aid-25-years-later.jhtml|title=Looking back at Live Aid 25 years later|publisher=[[MTV]]|date=13 July 2010|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> The BBC transmission truck blew a fuse during the band's set, stopping video from being broadcast. It resumed a short while later.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/witness/july/13/newsid_3041000/3041494.stm|title=On this day : 13 July|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> At the [[List of BRIT Awards ceremonies#1988|1988]] [[Brit Awards]], held at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in London, the band was honoured with the [[British Phonographic Industry]]'s Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>[http://www.brits.co.uk/artist/the-who "The Who"]. Brit Awards. Retrieved 3 February 2012</ref> They played a short set at the ceremony, which turned out to be the last time Jones played with the Who.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/kenney-jones-mn0000068047/biography|title=Kenney Jones&nbsp;– biography|first=Greg|last=Prato|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=30 August 2013}}</ref>

====1989 tour====
In 1989, the band embarked on a 25th anniversary ''The Kids Are Alright'' reunion tour. [[Simon Phillips]] played drums, and [[Steve Bolton|Steve "Boltz" Bolton]] played lead guitar. Townshend relegated himself to acoustic guitar and some electric rhythm guitar, claiming he did so to preserve his hearing.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=539}} Their two shows at Sullivan Stadium in Foxboro, Massachusetts, sold 100,000 tickets in less than eight hours, beating previous records set there by [[U2]] and [[David Bowie]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The Who Sell Out (Again)|first=Jeffrey |last=Ressner |work=Rolling Stone|date=15 June 1989 |page=20}}</ref> However, some critics slated the over-produced and expanded line-up of the tour, calling it "The Who on Ice",<ref name="greene"/> while AllMusic's [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] said the tour "tarnished the reputation of the Who almost irreparably".<ref name="jointogether"/> The 1989 reunion tour included most of ''Tommy'' with several guest stars, including [[Phil Collins]], [[Billy Idol]] and [[Elton John]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/live-featuring-rock-opera-tommy-mw0000267855|title=Live:Featuring Rock Opera Tommy|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref> A 2-CD live album, ''Join Together'', was released in 1990.<ref name="jointogether">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/join-together-mw0000206482|title=''Join Together''&nbsp;– The Who|first=Stephen Thomas|last=Erlewine|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref>

====Partial reunions====
In 1990, the Who were inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] museum.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=540}} The group have a featured collection in the museum, including one of Moon's velvet suits, a [[Warwick (company)|Warwick]] bass used by Entwistle, and a drum head dating from 1968.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rockhall.com/exhibits/featured-collections/the-who/|title=Featured Collections : The Who|publisher=Rock and Roll Hall of Fame|accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref>

In 1991, the Who recorded a cover of Elton John's "[[Saturday Night's Alright for Fighting]]" for the tribute album ''[[Two Rooms: Celebrating the Songs of Elton John & Bernie Taupin]]''. It was the last new studio recording to feature Entwistle. In 1994, Daltrey turned 50 and celebrated with two concerts at New York's [[Carnegie Hall]]. The shows included guest spots by Entwistle and Townshend. Although all three surviving original members of the Who attended, they did not appear on stage together except for during the finale, "Join Together", with the other guests. Daltrey toured that year with Entwistle, [[Zak Starkey]] on drums and [[Simon Townshend]] filling in for his brother as guitarist.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=542}}

===Re-formation===

====Revival of ''Quadrophenia''====
In 1996, Townshend, Entwistle and Daltrey performed ''Quadrophenia'' with guest stars at a concert in [[Hyde Park, London|Hyde Park]], with Zak Starkey as the drummer.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=543}} The performance was narrated by Phil Daniels, who had played Jimmy the Mod in the film. Despite technical difficulties the show was a success and led to a six-night residency at Madison Square Garden. The success of the ''Quadrophenia'' shows led to a [[The Who Tour 1996-1997|US and European tour through 1996 and 1997]].{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=543}} Townshend played mostly acoustic guitar, but eventually was persuaded to play some electric.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/ae/music/the-who-resurrects-its-other-rock-opera-quadrophenia-661109/|title=The Who resurrects its 'other' rock opera, 'Quadrophenia'|first=Scott|last=Mervis|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=8 November 2012|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> In 1998, [[VH1]] ranked the Who ninth in their list of the "100 Greatest Artists of Rock 'n' Roll".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1998/vh1artists.htm|title=VH1: 100 Greatest Artists of Rock & Roll|publisher=[[VH1]]|accessdate=22 November 2012}}</ref>

====Charity shows and Entwistle's death====
In late 1999, the Who performed in concert as a five-piece for the first time since 1985, with Bundrick on keyboards and Starkey on drums. The first show took place on 29 October 1999 in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] at the [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]].<ref name="greene">{{cite journal|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/flashback-the-who-strip-down-at-their-1999-comeback-show-20130226|title=Flashback: The Who Strip Down at their 1999 comeback show|first=Andy|last=Greene|journal=Rolling Stone|date=26 February 2013|accessdate=21 September 2013}}</ref> which was partially broadcast on TV, as well as the internet, and would later see release as the DVD ''[[The Vegas Job]]''. They then performed acoustic shows at [[Neil Young]]'s [[Bridge School Benefit]] at the [[Shoreline Amphitheatre]] in [[Mountain View, California]], on 30 and 31 October,<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/neil-young-the-who-pearl-jam-take-it-to-the-bridge-19991101|title=Neil Young, the Who, Pearl Jam, Take It to the Bridge|first=Denise|last=Sullivan|work=Rolling Stone|date=1 November 1999|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> followed by gigs at the [[House of Blues]] in Chicago.<ref name="official">{{cite web|url=http://thewho.com/history/|title=History&nbsp;– The Who|publisher=The Who (official site)|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> Finally, there were two Christmas charity shows on 22 and 23 December at the [[Shepherds Bush Empire]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.academy-music-group.co.uk/venue/venue.aspx?id=578|title=Shepherd's Bush Empire|publisher=Academy Music Group|accessdate=21 September 2013}}</ref> Critics were delighted to see the band back on form with a basic line-up comparable to the tours of the 1960s and 1970s. Andy Greene, writing in ''Rolling Stone'', claimed the 1999 tour to be even better than the final one with Moon in 1976.<ref name="greene"/>

The success of 1999 led to a US tour in 2000 from June to October, moving to the UK in October and November,<ref name="official"/> to generally favourable reviews.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sean|last=Piccoli|title=Great Generation|work=The Sun Sentinel|date=25 September 2000 |url=http://www.thewholive.de/details/index.php?id=243&Tracklisting=&GroupID=1&Tag=&Monat=&Jahr=2000&Stadt=&Halle=&LandID=0 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110719095355/http://www.thewholive.de/details/index.php?id=243&Tracklisting=&GroupID=1&Tag=&Monat=&Jahr=2000&Stadt=&Halle=&LandID=0|archivedate=19 April 2011}}</ref>  The final date was charity show on 27 November at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] for the Teenage Cancer trust, which included guest performances from Weller, [[Pearl Jam]]'s [[Eddie Vedder]], [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]]' [[Noel Gallagher]], [[Bryan Adams]] and [[Nigel Kennedy]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/249329/The-Who-Special-Guests-Live-at-the-Royal-Albert-Hall/overview|title=The Who & Special Guests: Live at the Royal Albert Hall (2000)|work=The New York Times|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> Stephen Tomas Erlewine described the Albert Hall gig as "an exceptional reunion concert".<ref name="alberthall">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/live-at-the-royal-albert-hall-mw0000036378|title=Live at the Royal Albert Hall|first=Stephen Thomas|last=Erlewine|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> The band performed [[the Concert for New York City]] at [[Madison Square Garden]] on 20 October 2001, which was dedicated to families of fallen New York City firemen and policemen who had lost their lives at the [[World Trade Center]] on [[September 11 Attacks|11 September 2001]].<ref name="usatoday200110">{{cite news|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/money/media/2001-10-19-concert.htm|title=Corporations put aside egos, rivalry to help out|first=David|last=Lieberman|work=USA Today|date=19 October 2001|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> The Who were also honoured with a [[Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award]] that year.<ref name="Grammy"/>

The Who played some concerts in the UK in early 2002, in preparation for a full US tour. On 27 June, the day before the tour was due to commence,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/1213203.stm|title=The Who bassist Entwistle dies|publisher=BBC News|date=28 June 2002|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> Entwistle was found dead at the [[Hard Rock Hotel and Casino (Las Vegas)|Hard Rock Hotel]] in Las Vegas. The cause was a heart attack in which [[cocaine]] was a contributing factor. He was 57.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2152761.stm |title=Cocaine 'killed The Who star' |publisher=BBC News |date=26 July 2002 |accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref>

====After Entwistle and ''Endless Wire''====
[[File:The Who 2007 -2-.JPG|left|thumb|The Who on Tour in 2007. L to R: [[Zak Starkey]], Daltrey, Townshend, and [[John "Rabbit" Bundrick]]]]

Entwistle's son, Christopher, gave a statement supporting the Who continuing the tour, which began at the [[Hollywood Bowl]] on 2 July with [[Pino Palladino]] replacing Entwistle as bassist. Townshend dedicated the show to Entwistle, which ended with a montage of pictures featuring him. The tour lasted until September.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/03/business/03hedge.html?pagewanted=all|title=The Who Spring Back And Start Their Tour|first=Bernard|last=Weinraub|work=The New York Times|date=3 July 2002|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> The loss of a founder member of the Who caused Townshend to re-evaluate his relationship with Daltrey, which had become strained several times over the band's career. He decided their friendship was important, and this ultimately led to writing and recording new material.<ref name="nyt20061029"/>

As part of a general plan to combat [[bootleg recording|bootlegging]], the band began to release the [[Encore Series 2002|Encore Series]] of officially released soundboard tapes via themusic.com. An official statement read "to satisfy this demand they have agreed to release their own official recordings to benefit worthy causes."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/74429/the-who-to-offer-live-bootlegs|title=The Who To offer Live Bootlegs|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=26 August 2002|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref>

In 2004, the Who released "Old Red Wine" and "Real Good Looking Boy" (with Pino Palladino and [[Greg Lake]], respectively, on bass guitar), as part of a singles anthology (''[[The Who: Then and Now]]''), and went on an [[The Who Tour 2004|18-date tour]] playing Japan, Australia, the UK and the US. Later that year, ''Rolling Stone'' ranked the Who No.&nbsp;29 on their list of the 100 Greatest Artists of All Time.<ref>{{cite news | title=The Immortals: The First Fifty | work=Rolling Stone | issue=946 | url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5939214/the_immortals_the_first_fifty | date=24 March 2004 | accessdate=3 January 2007}}</ref>

[[File:Zak Starkey2.jpg|thumb|[[Zak Starkey]] has been The Who's main drummer since 1994, and turned down an invitation to be a full-time member<ref name="townshend200612"/>]]

The Who announced in 2005 that a new album was being worked on. Townshend posted a novella called ''[[The Boy Who Heard Music]]'' on his blog, which developed into a mini-opera called ''[[Wire & Glass]]'', forming the basis for the album.<ref name="nyt20061029">{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/29/arts/music/29ligh.html?ref=thewho|title=24 Years Later, Believe It or Not, The Who's Next|first=Alan|last=Light|work=The New York Times|date=29 October 2006|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> ''[[Endless Wire (The Who album)|Endless Wire]]'' was released on 30 October 2006 (31 October in the US). It was the first full studio album of new material since 1982's ''[[It's Hard]]'' and contained the band's first mini-opera since "Rael" on 1967's ''[[The Who Sell Out]]''. ''Endless Wire'' reached No.&nbsp;7 on ''Billboard'' and No.&nbsp;9 in the [[UK Albums Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thewho.com/album/endless-wire/|title=Endless Wire|publisher=The Who (official site)|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> Starkey was invited to join Oasis in April 2006, and the Who in November 2006, but he declined, preferring to split his time between the two.<ref name="townshend200612">{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20070101222426/http://www.petetownshend.co.uk/diary/display.cfm?id=459&zone=diary|first=Pete|last=Townshend|authorlink=Pete Townshend|title=Zak and the Revision of History|publisher=Pete Townshend (official site)|date=4 December 2006|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref>

In November 2007, the documentary ''[[Amazing Journey: The Story of the Who]]'' was released. The documentary includes footage not in earlier documentaries, including film from the 1970 Leeds University appearance and the 1964 performance at the Railway Hotel when they were The High Numbers. ''Amazing Journey'' was nominated for a 2009 Grammy Award.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/2100-207_162-4647770.html|title=The 51st Annual Grammy Awards|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=22 November 2012}}</ref>

Since the release of ''Endless Wire'', the Who have continued to tour and receive awards on a regular basis. Highlights include performing on the [[Live 8 concert, London|London stage of the Live 8 concert]] in July 2005, winning the Freddie Mercury Lifetime Achievement Award in Live Music at the Vodafone music awards,<ref name="Vodafone">{{cite web|url=http://www.vodafonemusic.co.uk/awards/2006/winners.cfm|title=2006 Vodafone Live Music Awards|publisher=Vodafone|accessdate=16 May 2008}}</ref> performing at the [[BBC Radio 2 Electric Proms|BBC Electric Proms]] at the [[Roundhouse (venue)|Roundhouse]] in London,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/electricproms/2006/who/|title=Electric Proms&nbsp;– The Who|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref> headlining the [[Glastonbury Festival]]<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nme.com/news/glastonbury/29212|title=The Who close Glastonbury 2007|work=NME|accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref> and a return appearance at the Isle of Wight,<ref>{{cite news | author=Wolfson, Richard | title=Sheer genius |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK | url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2004/06/14/bmwight14.xml&sSheet=/arts/2004/06/15/ixmusicmain.html | date=14 June 2004 | accessdate=7 January 2007}}</ref> being honoured at the [[VH1 Rock Honors#2008|2008 ''VH1 Rock Honors'']] in Los Angeles,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,381391,00.html |title=The Who Gets 'Rock Honors' in Los Angeles |publisher=Fox News Channel |date=13 July 2008 |accessdate=24 November 2010}}</ref> appearing in the [[music video game]] ''Rock Band'',<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-who-rock-band-on-the-way-daltrey-drops-a-hint-20091029|title=The Who: Rock "The Who: Rock Band" On the Way? Daltrey Drops a Hint|work=Rolling Stone|date=29 October 2009|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> recognition at the [[Kennedy Center Honors]],<ref name="Kennedy Center Honors">{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2008/12/08/dave-grohl-chris-cornell-pay-tribute-to-the-who-at-the-kennedy-center-honors/ |title=Dave Grohl, Chris Cornell Pay Tribute to the Who at Kennedy Center |work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=24 November 2010}}</ref> and being the final act at the [[2012 Summer Olympics closing ceremony|closing ceremony]] of the London [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Olympic Games]].<ref name="olympics">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/london-2012/9470803/Olympics-closing-ceremony-playlist.html|title=Olympics closing ceremony: playlist|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=12 August 2012|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref>

In August 2009, Townshend announced on the Who's website that he is working on a new musical titled ''Floss'' which follows the story of an ageing rocker known as "Walter", some songs of which may appear on a future Who album.<ref>{{cite web|first=Daniel |last=Kreps |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2009/08/25/pete-townshend-writing-new-musical-songs-headed-for-who-lp/ |title=Pete Townshend Writing New Musical, Songs Headed for Who LP |work=Rolling Stone|date=25 August 2009 |accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref>

On 19 November 2012, the Who released the album ''[[Live at Hull]]'', the band's performance in Hull on 15 February 1970—the night after the ''Live at Leeds'' gig was recorded.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://store.universal-music.co.uk/restofworld/the-who/whovember-2012/icat/thewhowhovember2012/?utm_source=official-who-channels&utm_medium=official-who-channels&utm_campaign=whovember2012|title=Whovember 2012|publisher=Universal Music|date=24 October 2011|accessdate=8 November 2012}}</ref> The missing bass at the start of the gig was restored by using the recording from the Leeds gig and digitally realigning it.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/humberside/hi/people_and_places/newsid_9190000/9190474.stm|title=The Who: Live in Hull after a 40 year wait|publisher=BBC News|date=15 November 2010|accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref> A remastered mono mix of "My Generation" was also released as a single.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://thewho.com/story/christmas-comes-early-for-who-fans/|title=CHRISTMAS COMES EARLY FOR WHO FANS|publisher=The Who|date=12 October 2011|accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref>

====Quadrophenia and More====
{{main|Quadrophenia and More}}
[[File:The Who in Miami 2010-02-05.jpg|right|thumb|Roger Daltrey and Pete Townshend performing in Miami, Florida, on 5 February 2010]]

The Who performed ''Quadrophenia'' at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] on 30 March 2010 as part of the [[Teenage Cancer Trust]] series of 10 gigs. This one-off performance of the rock opera featured guest appearances from Vedder, [[Kasabian]]'s [[Tom Meighan]] and the [[London Symphony Orchestra]]'s [[Tom Norris (musician)|Tom Norris]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewho.com/index.php?module=news&news_item_id=409 |title=QUADROPHENIA AT THE ALBERT |publisher=The Who (official site)|date=6 April 2010 |accessdate=7 July 2010}}</ref> Townshend told ''Rolling Stone'' that the band had planned a tour for early 2010, but later stated this was jeopardised due to the return of his [[tinnitus]]. He is experimenting with a new in-ear monitoring system that was recommended to him by fellow rocker [[Neil Young]] and his audiologist.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2010/02/18/the-whos-future-uncertain-as-townshends-tinnitus-returns|title = The Who's Future Uncertain as Townshend's Tinnitus Returns |work=Rolling Stone| date = 18 February 2010 |  accessdate =18 February 2010}}</ref> The in-ear monitoring system was scheduled to be tested out at the ''Quadrophenia'' concert at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] on 30 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalalberthall.com/press/pressreleases/release.aspx?id=9660 |title=TCT 2010 |publisher=Royal Albert Hall |date=1 February 2010 |accessdate=7 July 2010}}</ref>

In July, Daltrey stated that they had acquired new equipment, including earpieces, that he and the band are learning to use to enable Townshend to perform. The Who hoped to tour again in 2011, with "a new show," according to Daltrey, or possibly a retooled stage presentation of ''Quadrophenia''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Graff |first=Gary |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/photos/live/957504/the-who-eyeing-spring-2011-quadrophenia-tour |title=The Who Eyeing Spring 2011 'Quadrophenia' Tour |work=Billboard  |date=6 July 2010 |accessdate=7 July 2010}}</ref> The tour was officially announced in July 2012,<ref name="thewho20120718">{{cite press release|url=http://thewho.com/story/tickets-on-sale-beginning-friday-july-20-general-public-on-sale-july-27 |title=THE WHO ANNOUNCE NORTH AMERICAN TOUR PERFORMING "QUADROPHENIA" PLUS WHO CLASSICS |publisher=Thewho.com |date=18 July 2012 |accessdate=18 July 2012}}</ref> and started on 1 November in [[Ottawa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ottawasun.com/2012/11/21/the-who-quadrophenia-and-more-in-ottawa|title=The Who Quadrophenia (and more) in Ottawa|work=Ottawa Sun|date=21 November 2012|accessdate=22 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.montrealgazette.com/entertainment/music/Concert+review+Bell+Centre+2012/7588198/story.html|title=The Who as explosive, stately, challenging as you remember|work=''The Gazette'' (Montreal)|date=21 November 2012|accessdate=22 November 2012}}</ref> Bundrick was not present for the tour, having been replaced by keyboardists [[Chris Stainton]], [[Loren Gold]] and [[Frank Simes]], the latter of which also acted as musical director.<ref name="thewho20120718"/> The tour moved to Europe and the UK in 2013, ending at the [[Wembley Arena]], London on 8 July.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thewho.com/blog/story/quadrophenia-tour-closes-with-press-and-fans-in-one-mind/|title=Quadrophenia Tour closes with Press and Fans in One Mind?|publisher=The Who (official site)|accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref>

====Future plans====
In October 2013, Townshend told the ''[[London Evening Standard]]'' that the Who would stage their final tour in 2015 and will perform in locations they have never performed previously.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gibsone|first=Harriet|url=http://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/oct/24/the-who-quit-touring-after-2015-pete-townshend|title=The Who Quit Touring After 2015|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=24 October 2013|accessdate=29 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-who/73397|title=The Who announce they will quit touring after 50th anniversary gig in 2015|work=NME|date=24 October 2013|accessdate=31 October 2013}}</ref> Daltrey later clarified that the tour is unrelated to the band's 50th anniversary—which actually occurred in 2013—and also indicated that he and Townshend were considering recording new material but would be emphasising their hits in their final stadium tour.<ref name="rs2015">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-who-to-launch-last-big-tour-in-2015-20131029 |title=The Who to Launch 'Last Big Tour' in 2015 |last=Greene |first=Andy |date=29 October 2013  |work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref> However, some journalists were suspicious of this being a genuine "final" tour, with the ''Daily Mirror'''s Johnny Sharp pointing out that the Who previously quit touring, supposedly for good, in 1982.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/johnny-sharp-popstars-quit-music-2647406|title=Popstars quit music just to make comebacks, it's predictable and lazy!|first=Johnny|last=Sharp|work=Daily Mirror|date=27 October 2013|accessdate=31 October 2013}}</ref>

==Musical style==
{{see also|The Who's musical equipment}}
{{Quote box
 |quote  =  The music of the Who can only be called rock & roll ... it is neither derivative of folk music nor the blues; the primary influence is rock & roll itself.
|source =— [[Jann Wenner]]{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=89}}
 |align = right
 |quoted = 1
 | width = 33%
}}
While the Who have been regarded primarily as a rock band, their style changed during the course of their career. The original group played a mixture of [[trad jazz]] and contemporary pop hits as the Detours, which evolved into R&B during 1963{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|pp=22,26}} and then to mod the following year.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|pp=38-39}} A distinctive part of the original band's sound was Entwistle's lead bass playing, while Townshend concentrated on rhythm and chords.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=24}} Entwistle's bass has been described as displaying "the strong influence of Rhythm and Blues".{{sfn|Campbell|2012|p=239}} Moon's arrival in the band further strengthened this reversal of traditional rock instrumentation, frequently playing lead parts on his drumkit.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=88}}

The group became pioneering users of the [[Marshall Stack]]. This arose from Townshend perceiving himself to be less technical than contemporary guitarists such as [[Eric Clapton]] and [[Jeff Beck]] and deciding to stand out visually instead. Entwistle was the first member to get two 4x12 [[Instrument amplifier#Standard amp|speaker cabinets]], quickly followed by Townshend. The group quickly integrated [[audio feedback|feedback]] as an integral part of the guitar sound.{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=43}} Moon stopped using the [[hi hat]] in 1966, and started using [[Premier]] drumkits on an exclusive basis.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=152}}

Like several other contemporary musicians, the group were influenced by the arrival of [[Jimi Hendrix]], particularly after the Who and the [[The Jimi Hendrix Experience|Experience]] met at Monterey. Fletcher described the latter as "so much better than the Who it was embarrassing".{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=189}} This, combined with lengthy touring, strengthened the band's sound. In the studio, they began to develop softer pieces, particularly on ''Tommy'' onwards, albeit with Moon's distinctive drumming.{{sfn|Fletcher|1998|p=232}} At the same time, they grew out of being a singles band to an album band, creating more than mere three-minute pop songs.{{sfn|Campbell|2012|p=239}} In the early 1970s, the band's sound developed to include [[synthesizer]]s, particularly on ''Quadrophenia'',{{sfn|Atkins|2000|p=177}} but by ''By Numbers'' the style had scaled back to more standard rock.{{sfn|Atkins|2000|p=222}}

Unlike several other major rock acts, the Who have featured prominent [[backing vocals]] within the group. After "I Can't Explain" used session men to sing backing vocals, Townshend and Entwistle resolved to do better themselves on subsequent releases, producing strong [[falsetto]] harmonies.<ref>{{cite book|title=Please Please Me : Sixties British Pop, Inside Out: Sixties British Pop, Inside Out|first=Gordon|last=Thompson|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2008|page=95|isbn=978-0-1997-1555-8}}</ref> Daltrey, Townshend and Entwistle all sang lead on various songs, with Moon joining in for the occasional number. ''Who's Next'' featured Daltrey and Townshend sharing the lead vocal on several songs, and biographer Dave Marsh considers the contrast between Daltrey's strong, guttural vocal and Townshend's higher and more gentle voice to be one of the album's highlights.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=386}}

==Legacy and influence==
[[File:Pete Townshend Windmill-(jha).jpg|thumb|left|165px|Pete Townshend does the [[guitar showmanship#Pete Townshend|windmill]] in 1976]]

The Who are one of the most influential rock groups of the 1960s and 1970s.<ref name="Britannica vid">{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/642975/the-Who|title=The Who|publisher=Britannica Online Encyclopedia|accessdate=16 May 2008}}</ref> The group has been credited with originating the "[[rock opera]]"<ref name="Britannica vid"/> and it made one of the first notable [[concept albums]]. Their contributions to rock iconography include the power chord,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/jan/12/childprotection.society2|title=Power chord pioneer's artful life|first=Charles|last=Shaar Murray|work=The Observer|date=12 January 2003|accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref> [[guitar showmanship|windmill strum]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thewho.com/blog/story/announcing-the-who-windmill-contest/|title=Announcing The Who Windmill Contest|publisher=The Who (official site)|date=3 June 2009|accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref> the [[Marshall Amplification#The Marshall Legacy|Marshall Stack]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/jim-marshall-guitar-amp-pioneer-who-earned-the-epithet-father-of-loud-7624764.html|title=Jim Marshall : Guitar amp pioneer who earned the epithet "Father of loud"|work=The Independent|date=7 April 2012|accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref> and the [[instrument destruction|guitar smash]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.gibson.com/News-Lifestyle/Features/en-us/smashing-guitars-0303.aspx|title=5 Ways to Destroy a Guitar: Hendrix, Townshend, Cobain, Blackmore & SRV Show You How|first=Ellen|last=Barnes|publisher=Gibson|date=3 March 2010|accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref> The band had an impact on fashion from their earliest days with their embrace of [[pop art]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Art Into Pop|first=Simon|last=Frith|first2=Howard|last2=Horne|publisher=Methuen|page=101|year=1987|isbn=978-0-416-41540-7}}</ref> and their use of the [[Union Flag|Union Jack]] for clothing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-20966371|title=The union jack: A very complex flag|first=Richard|last=Cable|publisher=BBC News|date=10 January 2013|accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref>

Many notable artists claim to be influenced by the Who. [[Bono]] of U2 said, "More than any other band, the Who are our role models."<ref name="The Who Kennedy Center"/> [[Brian May]] of [[Queen (band)|Queen]] said, "They were my inspiration."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.intellectualonly-mercury.ru/interview/The_Life_Of_Brian.htm |title=The Life of Brian|work=Guitar World|accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref> [[Wayne Coyne]] of [[the Flaming Lips]] said, "I already believed in rock & roll, but seeing the Who really made me feel it. I knew I had to become a musician after that."<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/wayne-coyne-the-who-gave-me-no-choice-20080717 |title=Wayne Coyne: "The Who Gave Me No Choice" |work=Rolling Stone|date=17 July 2008 |accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref> [[Geddy Lee]] of [[Rush (band)|Rush]] said, "They were really influential on our band in a big way."<ref>{{cite web|last=Brunner |first=Rob |url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2009/03/17/rush-i-love-you/ |title=Rush's Geddy Lee talks about 'I Love You, Man,' 'Colbert,' and their new compilation |work=Entertainment Weekly  |date=17 March 2009 |accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref> [[Pearl Jam]]'s [[Eddie Vedder]] said, "The one thing that disgusts me about the Who is the way they smashed through every door in the uncharted hallway of rock 'n' roll without leaving much more than some debris for the rest of us to lay claim to."<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Substitute: The Songs of The Who|publisher=Edel Records|id=0126242ERE|year=2001}}</ref> [[Jack Black]] has declared: "The Who are the greatest band of all time".<ref name="black">{{cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/44569/jack-black-the-who-are-the-greatest-band-of-all-time|title=Jack Black: 'The Who Are The Greatest Band Of All Time|publisher=Gigwise|date=14 July 2008|accessdate=24 September 2013}}</ref> A number of songs by the Who have been covered by various artists. The most commercially successful cover is by [[Elton John]], with "Pinball Wizard" peaking at No.7 in the UK.<ref>{{cite book|title=Rock movers & shakers|first=Daffyd|last=Rees|first=Luke|last=Crampton|year=1991|publisher=ABC-CLIO|page=278|isbn=978-0-87436-661-7}}</ref>

Due to their major influence in rock music, the Who have spawned a number of tribute bands. Daltrey has endorsed [[the Whodlums]], which regularly raises money for the [[Teenage Cancer Trust]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Roger Daltrey backs Newcastle tribute band |date=1 September 2010 |first=Katie |last=Davies |work=Evening Chronicle
|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/evening-chronicle-news/2010/09/01/roger-daltrey-backs-newcastle-tribute-band-72703-27178948|location=Newcastle upon Tyne |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=2Toots Scooter Club raising funds for Amble boy Brandon Ballance |date=3 June 2011|first=Rachel |last=Wearmouth |work=The Journal
|url=http://www.journallive.co.uk/north-east-news/todays-news/2011/06/03/2toots-scooter-club-raising-funds-for-amble-boy-brandon-ballance-61634-28812954/ |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref>

The Who's [[Mod (subculture)|mod]] genesis inspired [[mod revival]] bands such as [[the Jam]],<ref>[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine|Erlewine, Stephen Thomas]]. "[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=the-jam-p4585/biography|pure_url=yes}} The Jam: Biography]". AllMusic.</ref> as well as later bands of the [[Britpop]] wave in the mid-1990s, such as [[Blur (band)|Blur]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Azad |first=Bharat |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/musicblog/2007/aug/14/isdamonalbarnthenewdavid |title=Is Damon Albarn the new David Bowie? |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=14 August 2007 |accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref> and [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.experiencefestival.com/a/Britpop_-_Roots_and_Influences/id/620188 |title=Britpop Roots and Influences |publisher=Experiencefestival.com |accessdate=24 November 2010}}</ref> The band has also been called "The Godfathers of [[punk rock|Punk]]"<ref>{{cite book|title=Boy Culture: An Encyclopedia|editor1-first=Shirley R.|editor1-last=Steinberg|editor2-first=Michael|editor2-last=Kehler|publisher=ABC-CLIO|page=386|year=2010|isbn=978-0-313-35081-8}}</ref> and several [[punk rock]] bands including the Sex Pistols,{{sfn|Neill|Kent|2009|p=396}} the [[MC5]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guitar.com/articles/wayne-kramer-and-mc5-still-kickin |title=Wayne Kramer and the MC5&nbsp;– Still Kickin' |publisher=Guitar.com |accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref> [[The Stooges]],<ref>{{cite web|first=Andy |last=Greene |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-stooges-ron-asheton-remembered-20090106 |title=The Stooges' Ron Asheton Remembered |work=Rolling Stone|date=6 January 2009|accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref> the [[Ramones]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Browne |first=David |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,106547,00.html |title=State of the Art |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=15 April 2001 |accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref> and [[Green Day]], point to the Who as an influence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/articles/green-day-we-love-who-and-cheap-trick |title=Green Day talks to SPIN |work=Spin|date=11 May 2009 |accessdate=24 November 2010}}</ref>

In 1967, Townshend coined the term "[[power pop]]" to describe the Who's sixties singles.{{sfn|Marsh|1983|p=253}} [[Andy Summers]] of [[the Police]] lauded Townshend by saying "He more or less invented the [[power chord]], and you can hear a sort of pre-Zeppelin thing in the Who's Sixties work. So much of this stuff came from him."<ref>{{cite web|last=Summers |first=Andy |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-greatest-guitarists-20111123/pete-townshend-19691231|work=Rolling Stone|title=100 Greatest Guitarists: Pete Townshend|accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' magazine said in its "100 Greatest Singers" list that Daltrey "had an uncanny ability to adapt to whatever character songwriter Pete Townshend came up with". Similarly, Wayne Coyne of Flaming Lips said "You don't realize how great a singer Roger Daltrey is until you try to do it yourself".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-greatest-singers-of-all-time-19691231/roger-daltrey-19691231|work=Rolling Stone|title=100 Greatest Singers: Roger Daltrey |accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref> The Who's influence can also be seen in early incorporation of synthesisers, with ''Who's Next'' featuring the instrument prominently.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531/the-who-whos-next-20120524|title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time&nbsp;– Number 28|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref> Prominent [[synthpop]] act [[Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark]] drew influence from the Who on their 1991 hit single "[[Sailing on the Seven Seas]]".<ref>[[Andy McCluskey]] interview. ''[[ITV News Granada Reports|Granada Reports]]''. [[ITV Granada]]. July 1991. Presenter: "OMD...have enjoyed a career revival of late with the smash hit '[[Sailing on the Seven Seas]]' which was influenced by, of all things, ''rock'' groups like The Who and [[The Velvet Underground]]."</ref>

===Television, film and games===
All three versions of the American forensic drama ''CSI'' (''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]'', ''[[CSI: Miami]]'', and ''[[CSI: NY]]'') feature songs written and performed by the Who as theme songs, "[[Who Are You (song)|Who Are You]]", "[[Won't Get Fooled Again]]" and "[[Baba O'Riley]]" respectively.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/?id=VbJJhtvGVy0C&pg=PA110&dq=%22the+who%22+csi#v=onepage&q=%22the%20who%22%20csi&f=false|title=Reading CSI: Crime TV Under the Microscope|first=Michael|last=Allen|page=110|publisher=I.B.Tauris|year=2007|isbn=978-1-84511-428-2}}</ref> A fourth version of the drama ''CSI'' has been announced for the 2014–15 television season entitled ''[[CSI: Cyber]]''. The show's theme will once again be a Who song, "[[I Can See for Miles]]".<ref>{{cite web|last=Paton|first=Jamie|url=http://www.watchingthewasteland.com/2014/05/10/csi-cyber/|title=The CSI Franchise Rises Again With CSI: Cyber|publisher=Watching the Wastland|date=10 May 2014|accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref> The group's songs have featured in other popular TV series such as ''[[The Simpsons]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/shows/the-simpsons/a-tale-of-two-springfields-3805/ |title=''The Simpsons''&nbsp;– 'A Tale of Two Springfields' |publisher=tv.com |accessdate=3 September 2012}}</ref> and ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]'' (which featured an episode where the presenters were tasked with being roadies for the band).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topgear.com/uk/tv-show/series-8/episode-8|title=All the vans : Series 8, Episode 8|publisher=Top Gear (official website)|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref>

Rock-orientated movies such as ''[[Almost Famous]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://books.google.com/?id=fBEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA94&dq=%22the+who%22+%22almost+famous%22#v=onepage&q=%22the%20who%22%20%22almost%20famous%22&f=false|title='Almost Famous' CD A Souvenir of the '70s|first=Carla|last=Hay|work=Billboard|date=2 September 2000|page=94|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> ''[[School of Rock]]''<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://books.google.com/?id=IBEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA18&dq=%22the+who%22+%22school+of+rock%22+%22jack+black%22#v=onepage&q=%22the%20who%22%20%22school%20of%20rock%22%20%22jack%20black%22&f=false|title=Black Back From Media Blitz, Really Wants To play Ozzy|first=Carla|last=Hay|work=''Billboard|date=25 October 2003|page=18|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> and ''[[Tenacious D and the Pick of Destiny]]'' refer to the band and feature their songs,<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/?id=mUMLAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA270&dq=%22the+who%22+%22tenacious+d%22+%22pick+of+destiny%22#v=onepage&q=%22the%20who%22%20%22tenacious%20d%22%20%22pick%20of%20destiny%22&f=false|title=Cengage Advantage Books: Visual Storytelling|first=Ronald|last=Osgood|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-285-60709-2}}</ref> and other notable films have used the band's material in their soundtracks, including ''[[Apollo 13 (film)|Apollo 13]]'' (which used "I Can See For Miles")<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/apollo-13-mw0000644960|title=Music from the Motion Picture Apollo 13|first=Stephen Thomas|last=Erlewine|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=24 September 2013}}</ref> and ''[[Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me]]'' (for which the band re-recorded "My Generation").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/austin-powers-the-spy-who-shagged-me-mw0000666856|title=Original soundtrack&nbsp;– ''Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged'' Me|first=Gina|last=Boldman|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=24 September 2013}}</ref> Several of the band's tracks have appeared in ''[[Rock Band (video game)|Rock Band]]'' and its sequels. ''Rock Band 3'' contains twelve additional Who tracks that can be downloaded and used in the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockband.com/songs/artists/The+Who|title=The Who // Songs|publisher=Rock Band (official site)|accessdate=24 September 2013}}</ref>

==Awards and accolades==
[[File:Thewho liveatleeds.jpg|thumb|Townshend and Daltrey unveil a [[blue plaque]] at Leeds University on 17 June 2006, to commemorate their 1970 album ''Live at Leeds'']]

{{main|List of awards and nominations received by The Who}}
''TIME'' magazine wrote in 1979 that "No other group has ever pushed rock so far, or asked so much from it."<ref name="Time Magazine"/> ''Rolling Stone'' wrote: "Along with the Beatles and [[the Rolling Stones]], the Who complete the holy trinity of British rock."<ref name="The Who"/>

The Who's display at the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame describes them as "Prime contenders, in the minds of many, for the title of World's Greatest Rock Band."<ref name="MTV Montgomery">{{cite web|last=Montgomery |first=James |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1556171/artists-that-never-had-1.jhtml |title=Always Second Place? David Bowie, Public Enemy, Kiss Never Topped Charts |publisher=MTV |date=3 April 2007 |accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref> They received an award for Outstanding Contribution from the [[British Phonographic Industry]] in 1988<ref name="BPI">{{cite web|url=http://www.brits.co.uk/history/shows/1988|title=The BRITs 1988 |publisher=British Phonographic Industry |accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref> and from the [[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences|Grammy Foundation]] in 2001, for creative contributions of outstanding artistic significance to the field of recording.<ref name="Grammy">{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.org/recording-academy/awards/lifetime-awards |title=Grammy Lifetime Achievement Awards |publisher=National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences |date=8 February 2009 |accessdate=24 November 2010}}</ref> In 2008, Townshend and Daltrey were given [[Kennedy Center Honors]] for their enduring influence on popular culture.<ref name="The Who Kennedy Center"/>

==Band members==

{{Main|Members of the Who}}
